</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B24FFBBFF6CFBD3FD22DDCD" blockId="22.[192,1441,1027,1499]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFF6CFBD3FD2DDC0D" bold="true" box="[192,723,1027,1051]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Identification, taxonomy, and variation.</emphasis>
Average wingspan is approximately 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B24FFBBFB2EFBD3FB28DC0D" box="[1154,1238,1027,1051]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="56.0">56 mm</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFB72FBD4FA5EDC0D" baseAuthorityName="dos Passos and Grey" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[1246,1440,1027,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carolae">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFB72FBD4FA5EDC0D" box="[1246,1440,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Speyeria carolae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is generally darker and bears slightly different wing shape and coloration than those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFB74FBF4FAB0DC2D" baseAuthorityName="Behr" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1240,1358,1060,1083]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFB74FBF4FAB0DC2D" box="[1240,1358,1060,1083]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. coronis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFA2BFBF4FEF3DC4D" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zerene">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFA2BFBF4FEF3DC4D" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. zerene</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The dorsal color of both sexes is bright reddish-orange; the ventral forewing is heavily flushed with reddish-orange anteriorly to or beyond vein M3, and this is usually more extensive than on 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFA9BFBB4FA5EDC6D" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1852" box="[1335,1440,1124,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zerene">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFA9BFBB4FA5EDC6D" box="[1335,1440,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. zerene</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFF58FB54FE95DC8D" baseAuthorityName="Behr" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[244,363,1156,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFF58FB54FE95DC8D" box="[244,363,1156,1179]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. coronis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The ventral hindwing disc varies from reddish-brown to brown and the spots are moderately large. The spots range from silvered to mostly unsilvered. 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFC02FB74FB8CDCAD" baseAuthorityName="dos Passos and Grey" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[942,1138,1187,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carolae">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFC02FB74FB8CDCAD" box="[942,1138,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Speyeria carolae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been hypothesized to be an intermediate between 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFDBEFB14FD78DCCD" baseAuthorityName="Behr" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[530,646,1220,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coronis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFDBEFB14FD78DCCD" box="[530,646,1220,1243]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. coronis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFD13FB14FC35DCCD" authority="(Scott 1986 b)" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[703,971,1219,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zerene">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFD13FB14FCD6DCCD" box="[703,808,1220,1243]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. zerene</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFC9AFB13FC3ADCCD" author="Scott, J. A." box="[822,964,1219,1243]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" refId="ref44819" refString="Scott, J. A. 1986 b. The butterflies of North America: A natural history and field guide. Stanford University Press; Stanford, California. 583 p." type="book" year="1986">Scott 1986b</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and may represent an extant, remnant form of the ancestral lineage between both of these species. Formerly recognized as a subspecies within the coronis complex (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFE16FAD3FD0DDD0D" author="dos Passos, C. F. &amp; L. P. Grey" box="[442,755,1283,1307]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 6" refId="ref35781" refString="dos Passos, C. F., and L. P. Grey. 1942. Two new North American subspecies of Argynnis, with some revisional notes (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). American Museum Novitates 1214. 1 - 6." type="journal article" year="1942">dos Passos and Grey 1942</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFD51FAD3FCC5DD0D" author="dos Passos C. F. &amp; L. P. Grey" box="[765,827,1283,1307]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 30" refId="ref35903" refString="dos Passos C. F., and L. P. Grey. 1947. Systematic catalogue of Speyeria (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae) with designations of types and fixations of the type localities. American Museum Novitates 1370: 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="1947">1947</bibRefCitation>
), and later the zerene complex by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFB62FAD3FA5FDD0D" author="dos Passos, C. F." box="[1230,1441,1283,1307]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="209 - 225" refId="ref35724" refString="dos Passos, C. F. 1961. Taxonomic notes on some Nearctic Rhopalocera. 2. Papilionoidea. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 15: 209 - 225." type="journal article" year="1961">dos Passos (1961)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFF58FAF3FE63DD2D" author="Austin, G. T." box="[244,413,1315,1339]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="66 - 74" refId="ref33857" refString="Austin, G. T. 1981. The montane butterfly fauna of the Spring Range, Nevada. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 35: 66 - 74." type="journal article" year="1981">Austin (1981)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFE0BFAF4FDE1DD2D" baseAuthorityName="dos Passos and Grey" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[423,543,1315,1339]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carolae">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFE0BFAF4FDE1DD2D" box="[423,543,1315,1339]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. carolae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered a distinct species by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFC77FAF3FAEDDD2D" author="Emmel, T. C. &amp; G. T. Austin" box="[987,1299,1315,1339]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="443 - 450" refId="ref37849" refString="Emmel, T. C., and G. T. Austin. 1998. What is Argynnis carolae? The cytotaxonomy and systematic position of a Speyeria relic from Nevada (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). p. 443 - 450. In: T. C. Emmel (ed.). Systematics of western North American butterflies. Mariposa Press; Gainesville, Florida. 878 p." type="book chapter" year="1998">Emmel and Austin (1998)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFAE1FAF3FEF2DD4D" author="Austin, G. T." pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="629 - 640" refId="ref33956" refString="Austin, G. T. 1998. Type data for butterflies described from Nevada. p. 629 - 640. In: T. C. Emmel (ed.). Systematics of western North American butterflies. Mariposa Press; Gainesville, Florida. 878 p." type="book chapter" year="1998">Austin (1998)</bibRefCitation>
based on differences in wing patterns and chromosome numbers (but see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFBD0FA93FE40DD6D" author="North American Butterfly Association" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" refId="ref43208" refString="North American Butterfly Association. 2001. North American Butterfly Association (NABA) checklist and English names of North American butterflies, 2 nd Edition. North American Butterfly Association; Morristown, New Jersey. 36 p." type="book" year="2001">North American Butterfly Association 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFE67FAB3FD9FDD6D" author="Scott, J. A." box="[459,609,1379,1403]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref45004" refString="Scott, J. A. 2008 a. Corrections / reviews of 58 North American butterfly books. Papilio 19: 1 - 129." type="journal article" year="2008">Scott 2008a</bibRefCitation>
, p.54). The nearest 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFCF6FAB4FC3BDD6D" authorityName="Scudder" authorityYear="1872" box="[858,965,1380,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFCF6FAB4FC3BDD6D" box="[858,965,1380,1403]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Speyeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
population to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFB4AFAB4FA9FDD6D" baseAuthorityName="dos Passos and Grey" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[1254,1377,1379,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carolae">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFB4AFAB4FA9FDD6D" box="[1254,1377,1379,1403]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">S. carolae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in southwestern 
<collectingRegion id="4991F8327B24FFBBFEC0FA53FE50DD8D" box="[364,430,1411,1435]" country="United States of America" name="Utah" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Utah</collectingRegion>
, approximately 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B24FFBBFDDDFA53FD35DD8D" box="[625,715,1411,1435]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" unit="km" value="225.0">225 km</quantity>
to the northeast. The geographic isolation and the low probability of present-day gene flow and probable, precinctive larval host plant 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFB91FA73FAC3DDAD" baseAuthorityName="Emmel and Austin" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[1085,1341,1443,1467]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Violaceae" genus="Viola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="charlestonensis">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFB91FA73FAC3DDAD" box="[1085,1341,1443,1467]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Viola charlestonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
support full species status (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFE0AFA13FD31DDCD" author="Emmel, T. C. &amp; G. T. Austin" box="[422,719,1475,1499]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="443 - 450" refId="ref37849" refString="Emmel, T. C., and G. T. Austin. 1998. What is Argynnis carolae? The cytotaxonomy and systematic position of a Speyeria relic from Nevada (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). p. 443 - 450. In: T. C. Emmel (ed.). Systematics of western North American butterflies. Mariposa Press; Gainesville, Florida. 878 p." type="book chapter" year="1998">Emmel and Austin 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B24FFBBFF6CF9D3FB30DE4D" blockId="22.[192,1440,1539,1628]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFF6CF9D3FEE1DE0D" bold="true" box="[192,287,1539,1563]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Range.</emphasis>
Isolated in southern Nevada’s Spring Mountains (Clark County). 
<typeStatus id="54EE88727B24FFBBFB81F9D4FB97DE0A" box="[1069,1129,1540,1564]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Type</typeStatus>
material was taken in the Charleston Range between elevations of approximately 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B24FFBBFCDEF9F3FBCDDE2D" box="[882,1075,1571,1595]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5908" metricValueMax="3.3528" metricValueMin="1.8288" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" unit="ft" value="8.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="6.0">
<geoCoordinate id="EE6150177B24FFBBFCDEF9F3FC49DE2D" box="[882,951,1571,1595]" degrees="6,000" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" precision="55" value="6.0">6,000</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="EE6150177B24FFBBFC1BF9F3FBEFDE2D" box="[951,1041,1571,1595]" degrees="11,000" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" precision="55" value="-11.0">-11,000</geoCoordinate>
ft.
</quantity>
It is regarded as the most restricted 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D537B24FFBBFE88F994FE14DE4D" box="[292,490,1603,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFE88F994FE70DE4D" box="[292,398,1604,1627]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Speyeria</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in geographical range (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFCA8F993FC70DE4D" author="Howe, W. H." box="[772,910,1603,1627]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" refId="ref41056" refString="Howe, W. H. 1975. The butterflies of North America. Doubleday and Company, Inc.; Garden City, New York. 633 p." type="book" year="1975">Howe 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFC34F993FB3FDE4D" author="Emmel, T. C. &amp; G. T. Austin" box="[920,1217,1603,1627]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="443 - 450" refId="ref37849" refString="Emmel, T. C., and G. T. Austin. 1998. What is Argynnis carolae? The cytotaxonomy and systematic position of a Speyeria relic from Nevada (Lepidoptera: Nymphalidae). p. 443 - 450. In: T. C. Emmel (ed.). Systematics of western North American butterflies. Mariposa Press; Gainesville, Florida. 878 p." type="book chapter" year="1998">Emmel and Austin 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEA36D07B24FFBBFF6CF953FCD2DEAD" blockId="22.[192,1440,1667,1724]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="B921EAC27B24FFBBFF6CF953FE9BDE8D" bold="true" box="[192,357,1667,1691]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21">Life history.</emphasis>
Adults occur in dry forests, hillsides, meadows, and riparian habitats above 
<quantity id="4CAD9B357B24FFBBFB58F953FAA8DE8D" box="[1268,1366,1667,1691]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8288" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" unit="ft" value="6.0">6,000 ft.</quantity>
in the Spring Range (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFED8F973FDF2DEAD" author="Austin, G. T." box="[372,524,1699,1723]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="66 - 74" refId="ref33857" refString="Austin, G. T. 1981. The montane butterfly fauna of the Spring Range, Nevada. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 35: 66 - 74." type="journal article" year="1981">Austin 1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B217B24FFBBFDBAF973FCE1DEAD" author="Fleishman, E. &amp; D. D. Murphy &amp; G. T. Austin" box="[534,799,1699,1723]" pageId="22" pageNumber="21" pagination="89 - 95" refId="ref38924" refString="Fleishman, E., D. D. Murphy, and G. T. Austin. 2005. Biodiversity patterns of spring-associated butterflies in a Mojave desert mountain range. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 59: 89 - 95." type="journal article" year="2005">Fleishman et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
